SIMPLE: possess
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Possess
<hw>Pos*sess"</hw> <pr>(?; 277)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Possessed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>;
<pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Possessing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L.
<ets>possessus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>possidere</ets> to have, possess,
from an inseparable prep. (cf. <er>Position</er>) + <ets>sedere</ets> to
sit. See <er>Sit</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To occupy in person; to
hold or actually have in one's own keeping; to have and to
hold.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Houses and fields and vineyards shall be <qex>possessed</qex>
again in this land.</q> <rj><qau>Jer. xxxii. 15.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Yet beauty, though injurious, hath strange power,⟦br⟧
After offense returning, to regain⟦br⟧
Love once <qex>possessed</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To have the legal title to; to have a just right to;
to be master of; to own; to have; <as>as, to <ex>possess</ex> property,
an estate, a book</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I am yours, and all that I <qex>possess</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To obtain occupation or possession of; to
accomplish; to gain; to seize.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>How . . . to <qex>possess</qex> the purpose they desired.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To enter into and influence; to control the will of;
to fill; to affect; -- said especially of evil spirits, passions,
etc.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Weakness <xex>possesseth</xex> me.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Those which were <qex>possessed</qex> with devils.</q>
<rj><qau>Matt. iv. 24.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>For ten inspired, ten thousand are <qex>possessed</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Roscommon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To put in possession; to make the owner or holder of
property, power, knowledge, etc.; to acquaint; to inform; -- followed by
<xex>of</xex> or <xex>with</xex> before the thing possessed, and now
commonly used reflexively.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I have <qex>possessed</qex> your grace of what I purpose.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Record a gift . . . of all he dies <qex>possessed</qex>⟦br⟧
Unto his son.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We <qex>possessed</qex> our selves of the kingdom of Naples.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To <qex>possess</qex> our minds with an habitual good
intention.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To have; hold; occupy; control; own.</syn>
<usage> -- <er>Possess</er>, <er>Have</er>. <xex>Have</xex> is the more
general word. To <xex>possess</xex> denotes to <xex>have as a
property</xex>. It usually implies more permanence or definiteness of
control or ownership than is involved in <xex>having</xex>. A man does
not <xex>possess</xex> his wife and children: they are (so to speak)
part of himself. For the same reason, we <xex>have</xex> the faculties
of reason, understanding, will, sound judgment, etc.: they are exercises
of the mind, not <xex>possessions</xex>.</usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Possession</ent>⟦br⟧
